IT is not a considerable Time since the Revenues of the Commonwealth did not exceed an hundred and thirty Talents, yet none of your Citizens, who were capable of fitting out a Galley, or advancing whatever Sums were demanded for the public Service, ever held themselves acquitted of those Obliga- tions, because Money was not in exceeding Plenty. On the contrary, our Gallies were equipped‚ the Funds were support- ed, and every Thing neceffary provided. Since that Time, Fortune hath aested most gracioussy towards us 3 hath wrought many signal Benefits for this Republic‚ and raised your Reve- nues from one, to four hundred Talents, without Prejudice to the rich, but rather with their peculiar Advantage. For all our richest Citizens receive a certain Proportion of them, and with Justice receive.
